recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. The bird was in the new leaves in the canopy of a red oak ~30m away on the north edge of the grounds around the house.

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 100 Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

At 1:02 its chatter can be heard, and at 1:08 its trill.  A Red-eyed Vireo joined it in the tree and began to sing at about 1:33;  at 1:44 and 1:49 both birds' voices can be heard. recordings.rmk:
Recording was modified slightly to amplify the three elements of the call against the background (a 5dB increase was applied to these three parts of the recording). 
Bird was seen closely only from directly below. Bright yellow throat and chest transitioning to bright white belly. Impression of brownish wings, warbler-like bill and some black on the face, a lighter eye-ring. Perhaps light wing bars. Size estimated to be maybe 3/4 the size of a red-winged blackbird.
Recording taken on a street running through the swamp. Bird landed about 25' off the ground above me in branches of bare/dead tree directly overhead, sang its three part song, then flew 50' to the next bare/dead tree and repeated the song, then another 50-75' to a third tree where it repeated the song a third time before flying out of range.

recordings.loc: Pipeline Road, Soberania National Park
recordings.rmk: While not the loudest song in this recording, the song of the Yellow-throated Vireo is the most interesting at this location. The other species sing many times every day here, whereas this vireo (mostly here only during the northern winter) usually vocalizes its burry call and rarely sings its song. Here it does so at 0:06, 0:09, 0:12, 0:14, 0:20, 0:24, 0:30, and 0:43. Wing snaps of Golden-collared Manakin are at 0:20, 0:22, 0:27, 0:28, and 0:57. A Ringed Kingfisher flew overhead starting at 0:50.

recordings.loc: Boag Road (road allowance trail), East Gwillimbury, Regional Municipality of York, Ontario
recordings.rmk:
Recorded amidst songs from a Song Sparrow and a Red-eyed Vireo in a very buggy, wet mixed bush. Listen carefully for a quivery almost trilling sound, rising and falling (or sometimes just rising) around the 3, 8, 18 and 23 second points in the recording. These quivery trills were begging calls observed as being made by two Yellow-throated Vireo fledglings. Around the 27 second point, an adult male announces its arrival with its typical shrill song, bringing food to the begging fledglings. I had been hearing these quivery sounds for some time, unsure what was making them, but finally observed what was making the sounds, begging fledglings about 15 feet off the ground (unusually low for YTVI), about 20-25 feet off the trail where birders are to remain. One of the most exciting audio discoveries I've ever made!

My better recorder had malfunctioned, so unfortunately I was only able to use my iPhone 7 Plus. The WAV recording has been normalized to a setting of -3.
